00:00:34.290 --> 00:00:39.190
Welcome to the Library of
Congress Literacy Awards program

00:00:39.190 --> 00:00:44.690
to recognize best practices
in reading promotion.

00:00:44.690 --> 00:00:50.150
I'm Kathryn Mendenhall, Director
of National Programs here

00:00:50.150 --> 00:00:54.120
at the Library of Congress,
which is in the National

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:58.200
and International Outreach
Service Unit.

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:00.480
The Center for the Book,

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:05.020
which administers the
Literacy Awards program is also

00:01:05.020 --> 00:01:09.240 position:56%
organizational in this service unit.

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:18.640
You are all here to demonstrate
how your impassioned work can be

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:21.840
replicated and shared with others

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:28.570
to achieve the extraordinary
success we're celebrating today.

00:01:28.570 --> 00:01:35.090
Our hope is that new
partnerships will be formed,

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:41.560
new dialogue will be held, not
just with the Library of Congress,

00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:44.910
but among yourselves
and with each other

00:01:44.910 --> 00:01:50.340
so that you can see what others
are doing and use their ideas

00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:53.510
to make your programs even better.

00:01:53.510 --> 00:01:59.650
It's really a unique
opportunity to have all

00:01:59.650 --> 00:02:04.690 position:56%
of you here today from near and far.

00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:08.620
Since its founding in 1800,

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:12.360
the Library of Congress's
mission has been one

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:15.670
of disseminating knowledge.

00:02:15.670 --> 00:02:22.370
Thirty years ago, in transmitting
a report to Congress in response

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:27.040
to a congressional
resolution authorizing a study

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:33.700
of the changing role of the book
in the future, what the Librarian

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:38.380
of Congress at the time,
who was Daniel Boorstin,

00:02:38.380 --> 00:02:44.990
stated in his transmittal
letter is applicable today.

00:02:44.990 --> 00:02:50.810
He said, "What we do
about books and reading

00:02:50.810 --> 00:02:57.020
in the next decades will crucially
affect our citizen's opportunities

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:01.550
for enlightenment and
self-improvement,

00:03:01.550 --> 00:03:08.060
their ability to share in the
wisdom and delights of civilization

00:03:08.060 --> 00:03:13.270
and their capacity for
intelligent self-government.

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:18.730
There could be no more appropriate
effort to fulfill the hopes

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:24.570
of our nation's founders nor
any more appropriate celebration

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:28.630
of the Bicentennial
of our constitution

00:03:28.630 --> 00:03:33.270
than to aim to abolish illiteracy."

00:03:35.530 --> 00:03:41.800
The Literacy Awards
benefactor, David M. Rubenstein,

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:45.150
established these awards
with the idea the

00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:51.430
by recognizing outstanding literacy
efforts both in the United States

00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:56.700
and abroad, public
attention will be drawn

00:03:56.700 --> 00:04:00.820
to the continuing need
for literacy services.

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:05.230
