01:51:45.310 --> 01:51:48.020
in a very, very small world.

01:51:48.020 --> 01:51:52.370 position:56%
And when they do get to our schools,
they get exposure to sign language

01:51:52.370 --> 01:51:56.330
but they also don't get any
exposure when they go home again.

01:51:56.330 --> 01:51:59.550
So, that language is only
spoken in school time

01:51:59.550 --> 01:52:01.480
or while they're in session.

01:52:01.480 --> 01:52:03.280
Because most students
stay in hostiles.

01:52:03.280 --> 01:52:05.700
So, there's very little
reinforcement at home

01:52:05.700 --> 01:52:07.000
with sign language as well.

01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:10.050
We don't have parental
involvement because a lot

01:52:10.050 --> 01:52:14.070
of our parents are
uneducated themselves.

01:52:14.070 --> 01:52:17.820
So, the only source of sign
language is at the school.

01:52:17.820 --> 01:52:21.170
I'm going to skip through to
show you what we've built.

01:52:21.170 --> 01:52:27.390
This is just a quote that I fond
and I think a lot of people think

01:52:27.390 --> 01:52:30.760
that people who are
Deaf, "they've got eyes,

01:52:30.760 --> 01:52:32.060
they can read, they can write."

01:52:32.060 --> 01:52:34.730
but have you ever thought
of just the sound

01:52:34.730 --> 01:52:39.760
of A. It can be an A. It can
be an R. And we've been exposed

01:52:39.760 --> 01:52:41.220
to those sounds in utero.

01:52:41.220 --> 01:52:44.010
We start hearing when we
are 26 weeks in utero.

01:52:44.010 --> 01:52:47.000
We get exposure to our mom's voice

01:52:47.000 --> 01:52:49.660
and language develops
from there onwards.

01:52:49.660 --> 01:52:51.730
For a Deaf child, they
never get that exposure

01:52:51.730 --> 01:52:55.050
to the auditory element of sound.

01:52:55.050 --> 01:52:59.830
And we forget how important sound
and languages and the auditory part

01:52:59.830 --> 01:53:02.690
of that to reading, to
understand how to read.

01:53:02.690 --> 01:53:08.090
You have to hear it to know what it
sounds like to be able to read it.

01:53:08.090 --> 01:53:10.690
So, when I started my journey,
I was one of those people.

01:53:10.690 --> 01:53:11.990
I had no idea.

01:53:11.990 --> 01:53:13.960
I didn't know that Deaf people
couldn't read and write.

01:53:13.960 --> 01:53:16.750
I thought we're quickly going to
create an app, I'm going to put it

01:53:16.750 --> 01:53:19.720
on the app store and I'm going to
move on and create my other books.

01:53:19.720 --> 01:53:23.950
But the school entrapped
me, they entrapped my heart.

01:53:23.950 --> 01:53:29.950
And they've created a space where
I think I can do my life's work.

01:53:29.950 --> 01:53:33.270
These are some of the students at
Transylvania School for the Deaf.

01:53:33.270 --> 01:53:35.890
They are the most spirited
people I've ever seen.

01:53:35.890 --> 01:53:39.570
And don't ever think that a
Deaf school is a silent place.

01:53:39.570 --> 01:53:44.020
These children have got joy
and laughter and exuberance

01:53:44.020 --> 01:53:47.810
and you can see it in
them playing outside.

01:53:47.810 --> 01:53:50.500
These are one of my
grade four students

01:53:50.500 --> 01:53:52.490
that we tested the books on.

01:53:52.490 --> 01:53:55.620
So, initially when we started out
with the books, we created books

01:53:55.620 --> 01:53:57.590
for grade four and five students.

01:53:57.590 --> 01:54:02.600
And my daughter who's hearing
was grade one at the time.

01:54:02.600 --> 01:54:07.590
And we were testing that with her
reading levels to see where we were

01:54:07.590 --> 01:54:10.650
on the scale of grade one, grade
four, between the reading and --

01:54:10.650 --> 01:54:15.120
between the hearing and
non-hearing students.

01:54:15.120 --> 01:54:17.950
And these students were struggling
with a grade one level book.

01:54:17.950 --> 01:54:20.830
So much so that they had
almost no comprehension

01:54:20.830 --> 01:54:23.040
of what they were reading if
we gave them a paper book.

01:54:23.040 --> 01:54:25.720
But then we created these apps.

01:54:25.720 --> 01:54:27.310
I can skip through all of this.

01:54:27.310 --> 01:54:30.780
You'll see this is the first time
they had exposure to the iPads.

01:54:30.780 --> 01:54:34.180
I literally went in with 30 iPads
that we put down in front of them

01:54:34.180 --> 01:54:36.530
and they had never
seen the books before,

01:54:36.530 --> 01:54:38.370
they'd never seen an iPad before.

01:54:38.370 --> 01:54:42.050
And we showed them where the home
button was and we opened the apps

01:54:42.050 --> 01:54:43.380
and they started exploring.

01:54:43.380 --> 01:54:46.580 position:56%
So much so that they found things
that I didn't think they would find.

01:54:46.580 --> 01:54:49.520
They found things like pinching
in and pinching out [laughing].

01:54:49.520 --> 01:54:53.080
And I should have known because
these kids are gesture based.

01:54:53.080 --> 01:54:54.510
You know? They're going
to use their hands.

01:54:54.510 --> 01:54:59.970
They're going to use their skills
to communicate and find things.

01:54:59.970 --> 01:55:01.560
This is the book that we created.

01:55:01.560 --> 01:55:04.600
And you'll see that the
book is in my home language

01:55:04.600 --> 01:55:07.490
on the left side, in Afrikaans.

01:55:07.490 --> 01:55:11.810
And then on this side it is in
English and that is accompanied

01:55:11.810 --> 01:55:13.230
by South African Sign Language.

01:55:13.230 --> 01:55:16.710
So, this is a trilingual
book that we have created.

01:55:16.710 --> 01:55:18.350
We had to start with Afrikaans

01:55:18.350 --> 01:55:20.560
because the school
initially was only Afrikaans

01:55:20.560 --> 01:55:23.890
and used Afrikaans
based sign language.

01:55:23.890 --> 01:55:27.630 position:56%
But then South African Sign Language
became recognized by the government

01:55:27.630 --> 01:55:32.390
and we had to transition from
Afrikaans based sign language

01:55:32.390 --> 01:55:34.830
to English and South
African Sign Language.

01:55:34.830 --> 01:55:38.440 position:56%
So, we created the books in both of
the languages for the older students

01:55:38.440 --> 01:55:41.750
and the new younger students.

01:55:41.750 --> 01:55:46.110
So, I'm going to just play.

01:55:46.110 --> 01:55:47.470
&gt;&gt; The Big Carrot.

01:55:47.470 --> 01:55:48.770
&gt;&gt; And that's me [laughing].

01:55:48.770 --> 01:55:51.400
My person that was supposed to
narrate got lost and couldn't come

01:55:51.400 --> 01:55:54.150
to the day of the recording
so I had to do it.

01:55:54.150 --> 01:55:57.610
And, but we started out
by creating a picture --

01:55:57.610 --> 01:55:59.950
with animation introduction
of the characters.

01:55:59.950 --> 01:56:01.250
&gt;&gt; The farmer.

01:56:01.250 --> 01:56:02.550
The farmer's wife.

01:56:02.550 --> 01:56:05.320
&gt;&gt; You can just make
it a little bit -- ?

01:56:05.320 --> 01:56:06.630
&gt;&gt; They work very hard.

01:56:06.630 --> 01:56:10.340
&gt;&gt; And then over here the sign
language interpreter is telling the

01:56:10.340 --> 01:56:13.710
story in sign language, which
is a completely different syntax

01:56:13.710 --> 01:56:15.010
to English syntax.

01:56:15.010 --> 01:56:17.270
And the student can go back to that

01:56:17.270 --> 01:56:20.100
and keep rewatching
it as they go along.

01:56:20.100 --> 01:56:23.430
Those words, you'll see are
highlighted and if you touch them,

01:56:23.430 --> 01:56:27.960
it shows you both the sign
plus the object or the person

01:56:27.960 --> 01:56:30.980
or the action plus the
word underneath it,

01:56:30.980 --> 01:56:33.110
plus the finger spelling
which is Deaf ABCs.

01:56:33.110 --> 01:56:38.770
And we found that this was the most
effective way to make that link

01:56:38.770 --> 01:56:41.630
between English and
sing language and create

01:56:41.630 --> 01:56:46.670
that bilingual environment for
students to see all of the elements

01:56:46.670 --> 01:56:51.220
at once and being able to go back
to it as many times as they needed.

01:56:51.220 --> 01:56:54.610 position:56%
We couldn't have this on an autoplay
where you could just start and play

01:56:54.610 --> 01:56:57.150
through because that's what's
happening with their reading.

01:56:57.150 --> 01:56:58.450
It's autoplay.

01:56:58.450 --> 01:57:01.840
They'll read through it, but
there's no comprehension.

01:57:01.840 --> 01:57:05.570
By presenting it in this way,
students could go at their own pace

01:57:05.570 --> 01:57:07.370 position:56%
and they could work through the book

01:57:07.370 --> 01:57:11.020
and really absorb both
the sign language as well

01:57:11.020 --> 01:57:15.870
as the finger spelling as
well as the text spelling.

01:57:15.870 --> 01:57:20.080
And then make that connection
between the English syntax

01:57:20.080 --> 01:57:22.030
and the sign language syntax.

01:57:22.030 --> 01:57:26.150 position:56%
Just a simple example, we would say,
"The man is walking in the street."

01:57:26.150 --> 01:57:28.710
In sign language they would
say, "Man street walk."

01:57:28.710 --> 01:57:34.710 position:56%
So, when we have words in there like
"the" and "and" and "Up" and "wow!"

01:57:34.710 --> 01:57:36.010
and "oops!"

01:57:36.010 --> 01:57:39.430
those aren't words that
really exist in sign language

01:57:39.430 --> 01:57:43.240
and when they see those things,
they get stuck and they don't want

01:57:43.240 --> 01:57:44.540
to read because it's difficult

01:57:44.540 --> 01:57:45.920
because they don't
understand what it means.

01:57:45.920 --> 01:57:50.320
And they don't understand what
context that word is used in.

01:57:50.320 --> 01:57:54.380
So, we had to place all of
that in context with a parallel

01:57:54.380 --> 01:57:58.240
of sign language, with a
parallel of English next to it.

01:57:58.240 --> 01:58:00.750
So, those were the
books that we created.

01:58:00.750 --> 01:58:05.750
I'm proud to say that we created
this with a very, very small team.

01:58:05.750 --> 01:58:10.890
We've had over 18,000 downloads
all over the world actually.

01:58:10.890 --> 01:58:12.190
I'm surprised.

01:58:12.190 --> 01:58:17.520 position:56%
We've got some in Kazakhstan,
Russia, Bermuda, Jamaica, Australia.

01:58:17.520 --> 01:58:19.330
It's everywhere.

01:58:19.330 --> 01:58:22.940
And we've had a lot of interest
from the Pakistan government,

01:58:22.940 --> 01:58:27.540
the New Zealand Ministry for
the Deaf to create more books

01:58:27.540 --> 01:58:31.350
